Fault Tolerance :
	- Ability to continue operating without interruption
	- In Microservices each service is running independently, usually microservices communicate with each other, there might be a chance that one of the service may fail, because of that  entire system collapse which is not good
	- This means our network is not fault tolerance
	-  failure of one microservice should be limited to that microservice
	
Fault Tolerance Needed because of below reasons
 	- Fault Isolation
 	- Network Latency
 	- Deployment Issues
 	- Increased Complexity 
 	- Elasticity
 	- Tolerating External failures

 Resilience4J :
 
 	- Resilience Means
 		- Ability or capacity to recover quickly from difficulties
 		- Resilience exists to add fault tolerance to our microservice architecture
 		
 	Techniques:
 	
 		- Retries - Automatically retry certain number of times)- This will be useful if there temprory issue like network latency
 		- Rate Limiting - controlling number of request handled by service within time frame
 		- Bulkheads
 		- Circuit Breakers 
 		- Fallbacks - alternate options in case of failure
 		- Timeouts 
 		- Graceful Degradation
 
 - Resilience4J is a lightweight, easy to use fault tolerance library
 - Easy Integration with Spring boot
 - Built for functional programming paradigms
 - Resilience4J Modules :
 	- Retry Module : Retry Module easily enables to implement retry logic in our applications
 	- Rate Limiter : RateLimiter allows us to enforce restrictions and protect our services from too many requests
 	- Bulkhead : Isolates failures and prevents them from cascading through the system. 
 				 - Limit the amount of parallel executions or concurrent calls to prevent system resources from being exhausted
 	- CircuitBreaker - Used to prevent a network or service failure from cascading to other services
 						- If circuit breaker 'trips' or opens and prevents further calls to the service
 						- https://resilience4j.readme.io/docs/circuitbreaker
 	
